Problem Statement¶

Context:¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective:¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

Observation to Note

  • On average, the companies in the dataset have around 5,667 employees. However, the standard deviation of 22,877 indicates that there is a large variation in the number of employees across the companies, which is indicative of a highly dispersed or skewed distribution with several outliers.
  • Since the mean of 5667 is larger than the median of 2109 it suggests that the distribution of the "no_of_employees" variable is right-skewed. This means that the tail of the distribution extends towards larger values, and there are relatively few companies with a large number of employees as compared to the number of companies with a small number of employees.
  • The data also shows minimum No of Employees with a negative value. This is not possible in a practical sense. It may indicate data entry errors or other anomalies in the dataset. It would be necessary to take appropriate measures to correct or remove them before further analysis.
  • The data shows that there are companies in the dataset established between 1800 and 2016, with a mean of 1979. This indicates that the majority of the companies in the dataset were established in the 20th century.
  • There seems to be companies in the dataset with year of establishement 1800 (over 200 yars old). Again this value may be invalid and could be an outlier.
  • The prevailing wage data ranges from USD2.13 to USD319,210. The mean of USD74,455 indicates that the prevailing wage is relatively high, but the large standard deviation of 52,815 suggest that there is a wide range of wages across the companies in the dataset.
  • The mean prevailing wage for occupation is USD 74,455 while the median (~50th percentile of wages) is USD 70,308. This indicates, slight right skewness in the data set as well.
  • The minimum prevailing wage is 2.1367 which is a very low wage and something that needs to be looked at.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=True, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=True, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=10)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=10,
            xytext=(0, 3),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

### function to plot distributions wrt target

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

B7. The US government has established a prevailing wage to protect local talent and foreign workers. Let's analyze the data and see if the visa status changes with the prevailing wage¶

In [ ]:
data.groupby(["case_status"])["prevailing_wage"].describe()
Out[ ]:
count mean std min 25% 50% 75% max
case_status
Certified 17018.0000 77293.6192 52042.7156 2.1367 38375.3300 72486.2700 108879.1075 318446.0500
Denied 8462.0000 68748.6816 53890.1660 2.9561 23497.2950 65431.4600 105097.6400 319210.2700
In [ ]:
distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, "prevailing_wage", "case_status")

Observations

  • Based on the summary statistics provided, it appears that the mean prevailing wage for certified cases is higher than the mean prevailing wage for denied cases.
  • However, we may need to perform a hypothsis test to furher determine if there is a significant relationship between these variables.
  • The standard deviation of the prevailing wage is higher for certified cases than for denied cases, suggesting that the range of prevailing wages for certified cases is wider.

Using a two-sample t-test.

  • Ho = there is no difference in the mean prevailing wage between the two groups
  • Ha = there is a significant difference
In [ ]:
'''
equal_var parameter is set to False to indicate 
that we are assuming that the variances of the two groups are different.
ttest_ind() performs a two-sample t-test with unequal variances

syntax data.loc[row_labels, column_labels]
'''

import scipy.stats as stats

certified_wages = data.loc[data["case_status"] == "Certified", "prevailing_wage"]
denied_wages = data.loc[data["case_status"] == "Denied", "prevailing_wage"]

t_statistic, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(certified_wages, denied_wages, equal_var=False)

print("t-statistic:", t_statistic)
print("p-value:", p_value)

t-statistic: 12.05605927170979
p-value: 2.4940631935946944e-33
  • Based on the t-statistic of 12.06 and a p-value that is less than a chosen significance level of 0.05, we can conclude that there is a significant difference between the mean prevailing wages of certified and denied visa applications.
  • Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis that the mean prevailing wages are equal and conclude that the prevailing wage does have an impact on the visa application status.

cat-columns was declared under breakdown or verify the categorical data further

Encoding Categorical Data¶

  1. Machine learning algorithms typically work with numerical data, and cannot process categorical data directly. Therefore, we need to encode categorical data into numerical values to enable machine learning algorithms to work with them.

  2. Algorithms, such as decision trees and random forests, can handle categorical variables directly. Hence we will only encode some of the columns as below.

    • We will encode the following categrical variable columns except case_status which will be done under Data Split : has_job_experience, requires_job_training, full_time_position and education_of_employee (because it has a natural order or hierarchy)
In [ ]:
# transform has_job_experience, requires_job_training and full_time_position
# Replace 'Y' with 1 and 'N' with 0

# Select the columns to encode and replace 'Y' with 1 and 'N' with 0
data[['has_job_experience', 'requires_job_training', 'full_time_position']] = data[['has_job_experience', 'requires_job_training', 'full_time_position']].replace({'Y': 1, 'N': 0})

# transform education_of_employee by hierarchy
# Use a lambda function to replace the education categories with numerical values
data['education_of_employee'] = data['education_of_employee'].apply(
    lambda x: 1 if x == 'High School' else (2 if x == "Bachelor's" else (3 if x == "Master's" else 4)))

Student Note :

Steps for comparing the performance metrics between various models:

  1. Split the dataset into training and testing sets.
  2. Choose different models to build and train them on the training set.
  3. Evaluate the performance of each model on the testing set using appropriate performance metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, AUC-ROC, etc.
  4. Compare the performance metrics of each model to determine the best performing model.
  5. Perform cross-validation to validate the model's performance.
  6. Fine-tune the hyperparameters of the best performing model using grid search or random search.
  7. Re-evaluate the performance of the tuned model and compare it to the performance of the other models.
  8. Choose the best model based on the performance metrics for deployment/use

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Model predicts that the visa application will get certified but in reality, the visa application should get denied.
  2. Model predicts that the visa application will not get certified but in reality, the visa application should get certified.

Which case is more important?¶

  • Both the cases are important as:

  • If a visa is certified when it had to be denied a wrong employee will get the job position while US citizens will miss the opportunity to work on that position.

  • If a visa is denied when it had to be certified the U.S. will lose a suitable human resource that can contribute to the economy.

How to reduce the losses?¶

  • F1 Score can be used a the metric for evaluation of the model, greater the F1 score higher are the chances of minimizing False Negatives and False Positives.
  • We will use balanced class weights so that model focuses equally on both classes.

First, let's create functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model.¶

  • The model_performance_classification_sklearn function will be used to check the model performance of models.
  • The confusion_matrix_sklearn function will be used to plot the confusion matrix.
In [ ]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn


def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [ ]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

  • The provided information shows the performance of a decision tree classifier that was trained with imbalanced classes, where the negative class (0) represents 33.21% of the training data and the positive class (1) represents 66.79% of the training data.
  • From the training performance, we can see that
    • the model is able to achieve a perfect accuracy of 1.0 for accuracy, recall, precision, and F1-score. This is likely due to reasons that the training data is highly imbalanced, with the positive class being over twice as large as the negative class and
    • the classifier is able to predict all the training examples correctly.
    • This could be an indication of overfitting, where the model has memorized the training data and may not generalize well to new data.

  • On the test set, the accuracy was 0.6512, indicating that the classifier correctly predicted the class of only 65.12% of the test instances. The recall was 0.7455, indicating that the classifier correctly identified 74.55% of the positive instances in the test set. The precision was 0.7357, indicating that of all the instances predicted as positive by the classifier, only 73.57% were actually positive. The F1-score was 0.7406, which is the harmonic mean of the precision and recall.

    • the testing performance of the model is not as good as the training performance, which is expected. This also indicates an overfitting since the performance metric is significantly better on the training dataset than on the testing dataset.

    • We can improve model performance by hyperparameter tuning

Confusion Matrix Inference

The confusion matrix for the test set shows that the classifier predicted the true negative class (0) for 15.33% of the instances, while predicting the true positive class (1) for 49.79% of the instances. This indicates that the classifier is heavily biased towards predicting the positive class, which is likely due to the class imbalance in the training data.

  • TN (True Negatives): Applicant visa was denied and the model predicted denial. (0-0)
  • FP (False Positives): Applicant visa was denied and the model predicted approval. (0-1)
  • FN (False Negatives): Applicant visa was approved and the model predicted denied. (1-0)
  • TP (True Positives): Applicant visa was approved and the model predicted approval. (1-1)

In summary, while the decision tree classifier achieved perfect performance on the imbalanced training data, it did not generalize well to the test data, suggesting that the classifier may be overfitting to the training data.

Student Notes : Summary comparison of the 3 models so far

a. Decision Tree is a simple model that is easy to interpret and understand where the data is split based on a set of rules that can be visualized as a tree structure. However, it is prone to overfitting, which means it may perform well on the training data but may not generalize well on the test data.

b. Bagging Classifier is an ensemble learning model that combines multiple models trained on different subsets of the data with replacement to improve the performance. The predictions from each model are then combined to get the final prediction. Bagging can reduce overfitting by combining multiple models. We saw that bagging gave better performance metrics above

c. Random Forest is another ensemble learning model that is similar to Bagging, but it uses a subset of features to split the data at each node of the Decision Tree. It combines multiple decision trees to improve performance, by randomly selecting a subset of features and data to build each tree, reducing overfitting. The final prediction is made up by combining the predictions from each tree.

This suggests that the model may be overfitting to some extent, but still performs reasonably well on unseen data.

Summary Comparison between the three models as far

  • From the performance metrics on both train and test data, it can be seen that the Decision Tree model has a perfect accuracy of 1.0 on the training data, which is indicative of overfitting. After tuning the hyperparameters of the Decision Tree, the accuracy decreased slightly but the model's overall performance improved.
  • On the other hand, Bagging Classifier and Random Forest models performed better than the Decision Tree model, with relatively high accuracy, recall, precision, and F1 scores on both the training and test data.
  • After tuning the hyperparameters of both Bagging Classifier and Random Forest models, the performance on the test data improved with the Bagging Classifier model having the highest accuracy, recall, and F1 scores among the three models.

Business Insights and Recommendations

EDA Insights¶

Trend (EDA) Observation with regards to H1B Visa certification in the USA :

  1. Education does have a significant impact on visa certification. We can observe that the higher the level of education received, the higher the number of visa applications certified. The percentage of certified visa applications is highest for applicants with a Doctorate degree (87.23%) followed by Master's (78.63%) and Bachelor's (62.21%).
  2. Having work experience seems to have a positive impact on visa certification. Among applicants with work experience, 74.48% were certified and 25.52% were denied. However, among applicants without work experience, only 56.13% were certified and 43.87% were denied. We could improve the dataset with more quality information to give better results. Recommendations are given below.
  3. A large percentage of visa applicants, about 88%, do not require job training. This again contributes to the visa certification and complements the above point as well. Skilled and experienced foreign workers in their chosen field would potentially save US employers time and money in terms of training and onboarding.
  4. Unit_of_wage is an important attribute that can influence case statuses. Comparing the monthly and yearly prevailing wages in the data provided, we can see that the mean prevailing wage rate for Year is lower than the mean prevailing wage rate for Month. This suggests that applicants who are offered a monthly prevailing wage rate may have a higher chance of getting their visa approved as they are being offered a higher wage rate than applicants with a yearly wage rate.
  5. In terms of continents, Asia had the highest number of visa applications (16,861 cases) compared to Europe (3,732 cases). However, Europe had the highest percentage of certified cases (79.23%) compared to Asia (65.31%). Generally, all continents had higher percentage of certified cases than denied cases, indicating that the majority of visa applications were successful.
  6. Regarding the analysis of regions and visa case status, we can see that the Midwest region (75.53%, ) has the highest percentage of certifications among the regions, followed by the South (70.02%.).

Some potential areas for further investigation which could be included in the dataset, and which can provide valuable insights in machine learning modeling and in OFLC's decision-making process when it comes to certifying or denying visa applications are:

  1. Type or quality of work experience: Instead of just having or not having work experience, you can consider including more specific information about the type or quality of work experience. For example, the industry of employment, length of employment, duration of work experience (length of time the applicant has worked in their previous roles as longer tenures may be viewed more positively by adjudicators).
  2. Employer characteristics: The current dataset includes information about the employer's size, but other information such as the industry or location of the employer could also be included. Certain industries or geographic areas may have higher demand for certain types of visas.
  3. Language proficiency: This could include information about the applicant's proficiency in English or other languages, which may be important for certain types of work or in certain locations.
  4. Education field: The current dataset includes information about the employee's education level, but more detailed information about the field of study, their GPA could also be included as it would help provide a more nuanced understanding of an applicant's qualifications and improve the accuracy of visa certification predictions. Also certain fields of study may be more in demand than others, leading to higher approval rates for those with relevant degrees.
  5. Country of origin: This could include information about the applicant's home country, as certain countries may have different visa requirements or be subject to different levels of scrutiny.

By including these additional features in the dataset, the machine learning model may be better able to identify patterns and make more accurate predictions about visa certification. Reasons are :

  1. Feature selection: These breakdowns can help identify important features that can be used as inputs to the machine learning model to predict the likelihood of visa approval. For example, the prevailing wage rate for a particular occupation or industry can be an important predictor of visa approval, and in return can improve the model's accuracy.
  2. Model training: By including these features in the dataset, the machine learning model can be trained on a more diverse set of data, which can improve its ability to generalize and make accurate predictions on new data.
  3. Model evaluation: These breakdowns can be used to evaluate the performance of the machine learning model by comparing its predictions to the actual outcomes in different occupational, geographic, and industry contexts. This can help identify areas where the model may be overfitting or underfitting the data and suggest ways to improve its accuracy.

However, it's important to keep in mind that including too many features could lead to overfitting, so it's important to carefully select the most relevant features and regularly evaluate the model's performance.
